Research Summary: This study evaluates the use of machine learning models to predict fetal health using CTG data, incorporating fetal heart rate, uterine contractions, and maternal blood pressure. The models applied include LightGBM, Random Forests, and TabNet, achieving high accuracies between 93% and 98.31%.

This study emphasizes ML models for classifying fetal health using CTG data. Models such as Random Forests, Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, Support Vector Classifiers, Voting Classes, and K-Nearest Neighbours were used. Random Forest achieved the highest accuracy of 93%.
Used Machine Learning Models: Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Decision Trees, SVC, Voting Classifiers, K-NN

Research Summary: The research investigates using machine learning models for fetal health classification, including ultrasound images. XGBoost and Random Forest were utilized, with Random Forest performing best for normal and suspect classes. The Random Forest model's predictions were interpreted using Explainable AI (XAI).
Best Accuracy Model's Name with Accuracy: Random Forest (best precision for normal and suspect classes)

Research Summary: This work focuses on the early identification of potential health risks for mothers and fetuses using machine learning to improve prenatal care. The study examines how ML can be used to predict fetal health and reduce mortality rates.
Used Machine Learning Models: XGBoost, Random Forest, Decision Trees, SVM, Neural Networks

Research Summary: This study uses supervised machine learning models to classify 2300 CTG exam records with 21 attributes. It compares classifiers such as K-NN, Linear SVM, Naive Bayes, Decision Tree, and Bayesian Networks. AdaBoost with Random Forest achieved the highest accuracy of 94.7%.
Used Machine Learning Models: K-NN, Linear SVM, Naive Bayes, Decision Tree, Bayesian Networks
